WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.341 --> 00:00:02.924
(upbeat music)

2
00:00:08.850 --> 00:00:10.950
<v ->And we're going to start this morning</v>

3
00:00:10.950 --> 00:00:13.800
as we look at basically what we do

4
00:00:13.800 --> 00:00:16.770
in terms of care every single day,

5
00:00:16.770 --> 00:00:18.240
which is health promotion and prevention.

6
00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:19.620
Now, I have nothing to disclose

7
00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:21.690
that in any way is gonna provide,

8
00:00:21.690 --> 00:00:24.180
present any bias in the information.

9
00:00:24.180 --> 00:00:25.380
We're gonna look at health promotion,

10
00:00:25.380 --> 00:00:26.490
prevention, and screening.

11
00:00:26.490 --> 00:00:27.690
The three leading causes

12
00:00:27.690 --> 00:00:30.420
of preventable morbidity and mortality.

13
00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:32.460
How do we counsel patients?

14
00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:36.330
And how do we reinforce the necessity of patient education,

15
00:00:36.330 --> 00:00:37.867
which is a lot of what we're doing today.

16
00:00:37.867 --> 00:00:39.570
"What do you mean, Dr. Weismiller?

17
00:00:39.570 --> 00:00:41.520
You're not gonna be doing a clinical breast exam

18
00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:42.870
to screen for cancer.

19
00:00:42.870 --> 00:00:45.180
And I don't need screening for cervical dysplasia.

20
00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:46.800
And I don't need a bimanual exam.

21
00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:48.177
Are you a doctor?"

22
00:00:49.590 --> 00:00:51.790
I am. What arm do you want your flu shot in?

23
00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:54.090
Okay, so there's a lot

24
00:00:54.090 --> 00:00:56.973
of education going on here constantly.

25
00:00:57.900 --> 00:01:01.230
Okay, so if we think about health promotion,

26
00:01:01.230 --> 00:01:02.790
most of this is going to revolve

27
00:01:02.790 --> 00:01:05.010
around lifestyle modification.

28
00:01:05.010 --> 00:01:06.810
And we're gonna look at the three leading causes

29
00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:10.560
of preventable morbidity and mortality in the US.

30
00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:12.090
Because everybody's coming in thinking,

31
00:01:12.090 --> 00:01:14.553
well, I need this, I need this, I need that.

32
00:01:15.420 --> 00:01:18.090
But your responsibility, my responsibility,

33
00:01:18.090 --> 00:01:21.420
because 60% to 70% of my week,

34
00:01:21.420 --> 00:01:25.030
every single week, I'm directly seeing patients

35
00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:29.010
and I'm taking the science that's available to me

36
00:01:29.010 --> 00:01:31.650
and helping that patient make the best healthcare decision.

37
00:01:31.650 --> 00:01:34.260
Where I feel strongly, I let the patient know that.

38
00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:37.080
But my responsibility is to not make the decision,

39
00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:39.213
but help them make the best decision.

40
00:01:41.190 --> 00:01:44.490
Now, every individual though comes

41
00:01:44.490 --> 00:01:46.203
with a complete background.

42
00:01:47.550 --> 00:01:49.290
And if you think about it,

43
00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:51.330
I had a patient who's in his forties.

44
00:01:51.330 --> 00:01:55.293
He looked on the Nevada Vaccine Registry.

45
00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:57.810
If I ever become Surgeon General,

46
00:01:57.810 --> 00:01:59.400
there'll be a national registry.

47
00:01:59.400 --> 00:02:00.840
No longer state registries.

48
00:02:00.840 --> 00:02:02.370
But he was looking on there.

49
00:02:02.370 --> 00:02:04.470
And it showed that way back in like,

50
00:02:04.470 --> 00:02:09.470
I don't know, 1990, he should have had a chickenpox vaccine.

51
00:02:09.540 --> 00:02:11.223
He's 40 something now.

52
00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:14.850
He goes to the pharmacy.

53
00:02:14.850 --> 00:02:16.850
And they gave him a chicken pox vaccine.

54
00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:22.380
I'm like, you didn't need that.

55
00:02:22.380 --> 00:02:24.127
Why did the pharmacist give you that?

56
00:02:24.127 --> 00:02:26.100
"Well, it said I needed it."

57
00:02:26.100 --> 00:02:29.700
Okay, well, that's why you need somebody working with you.

58
00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:31.350
Because otherwise, you just check things off

59
00:02:31.350 --> 00:02:33.847
and say, "I need this, this, this, and this."

60
00:02:33.847 --> 00:02:34.920
"Well, why didn't I need it?"

61
00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:35.887
Because you've been exposed.

62
00:02:35.887 --> 00:02:37.560
"I've never had chickenpox."

63
00:02:37.560 --> 00:02:42.560
By the age of 45, 99.9999% of people have been exposed.

64
00:02:42.780 --> 00:02:44.100
That's why we don't check a titer

65
00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:46.053
before we give you the SHINGRIX.

66
00:02:47.640 --> 00:02:49.140
If you look at pregnant women,

67
00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:51.570
women of reproductive age, "Oh, I didn't have,

68
00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:53.790
I've never had chickenpox and I got exposed."

69
00:02:53.790 --> 00:02:55.860
We'd always check a titer before we give VZIG

70
00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:57.603
because 90% will be seropositive.

71
00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.373
Okay, secondary prevention.

72
00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:06.930
That's where we're going to find something early,

73
00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:10.680
intervene, and change the outcome.

74
00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:13.110
Tertiary prevention, we spend a lot of time

75
00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:14.340
with in academic health centers.

76
00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:15.600
You know, you got a bad disease.

77
00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.340
We're trying to maximize function

78
00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:19.380
and minimize further compromise.

79
00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:20.910
And then quaternary prevention

80
00:03:20.910 --> 00:03:22.170
is the newest kid on the block.

81
00:03:22.170 --> 00:03:25.170
This is a set of health activities to mitigate

82
00:03:25.170 --> 00:03:28.470
or avoid the consequences of unnecessary intervention.

83
00:03:28.470 --> 00:03:32.880
Of course, this is what I refer to as first doing no harm.

84
00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:36.123
Now, here's examples of quaternary prevention.

85
00:03:37.110 --> 00:03:42.110
You know, it sounds like a UTI in that 52-year-old woman.

86
00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:46.050
But I haven't done a UA or urine culture.

87
00:03:46.050 --> 00:03:46.883
I just treat.

88
00:03:47.910 --> 00:03:50.430
Don't routinely recommend home glucose monitoring

89
00:03:50.430 --> 00:03:51.960
for patients who have type II diabetes

90
00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:52.860
and they're not on insulin.

91
00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:53.910
What are they doing with that?

92
00:03:53.910 --> 00:03:55.200
You've seen 'em come in.

93
00:03:55.200 --> 00:03:56.370
Tons of numbers.

94
00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:57.690
Oh, yeah. They look all good.

95
00:03:57.690 --> 00:03:59.220
Yep, good.

96
00:03:59.220 --> 00:04:01.710
Avoiding unnecessary screening.

97
00:04:01.710 --> 00:04:03.990
You know, screening a woman who's 80

98
00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:08.010
for cervical dysplasia or, you know,

99
00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:09.330
doing a stool-based study

100
00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:11.943
and they just had a colonoscopy last year.

101
00:04:12.930 --> 00:04:14.943
Okay, that's all unnecessary.

102
00:04:16.950 --> 00:04:19.410
Avoiding admission or preoperative chest x-rays.

103
00:04:19.410 --> 00:04:20.970
Both the American College of Radiology

104
00:04:20.970 --> 00:04:22.410
and the American College of Surgery say

105
00:04:22.410 --> 00:04:25.140
before elective surgery not involving the chest,

106
00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:26.940
you should not do a preoperative chest x-ray.

107
00:04:26.940 --> 00:04:29.310
It doesn't change the outcome of the procedure.

108
00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:31.980
It advances further radiation,

109
00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:33.720
therefore gives them something else,

110
00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:35.343
and doesn't change the outcome.

111
00:04:36.870 --> 00:04:38.130
Hmm.

112
00:04:38.130 --> 00:04:39.180
And don't place women,

113
00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:41.100
even those at high risk, on activity restriction

114
00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:43.020
to prevent preterm birth.

115
00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:44.420
Doesn't make any difference.

116
00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:49.560
Creates more anxiety for them and they'll get a DVT.

117
00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:51.930
But it doesn't change the outcome of the preterm birth.

118
00:04:51.930 --> 00:04:53.970
So those are all examples of quarternary prevention.

119
00:04:53.970 --> 00:04:56.070
Now, some of you are probably familiar with Choosing Wisely.

120
00:04:56.070 --> 00:04:57.620
Who's heard of Choosing Wisely?

121
00:04:59.326 --> 00:05:00.180
Oh, okay.

122
00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:02.070
You guys need to come to Family Medicine Update.

123
00:05:02.070 --> 00:05:04.470
Okay, this has probably been the biggest advance

124
00:05:04.470 --> 00:05:07.860
in coronary prevention put forward in the last decade.

125
00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:09.720
This is the American Board of Internal Medicine.

126
00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:11.640
They're just winding this down.

127
00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:15.000
And all of the Choosing Wisely statements are now moving on

128
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.470
to each homepage of an organization.

129
00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:22.200
But this was an initiative by the ABIM

130
00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:26.400
to have a national dialogue promoting conversation supported

131
00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:28.020
by evidence, not duplicative,

132
00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:30.243
free from harm, and truly necessary.

133
00:05:31.860 --> 00:05:34.050
Choosing requires us

134
00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:37.140
to have some judgment to set priorities.

135
00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:39.120
Without it, everything just looks the same.

136
00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:42.183
And that just becomes an emergency to do right this second.

137
00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:46.500
So with Choosing Wisely, what started out

138
00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:48.930
with 45 statements now has

139
00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:51.483
over 700 statements of what not to do.

140
00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:55.230
It started with five organizations.

141
00:05:55.230 --> 00:05:56.130
Now there are 80.

142
00:05:56.130 --> 00:05:58.680
Every American College of.

143
00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:01.440
And there are now 30 countries

144
00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:03.570
which have a Choosing Wisely campaign.

145
00:06:03.570 --> 00:06:05.250
We are just 1 of 30.

146
00:06:05.250 --> 00:06:07.383
And this was started just a decade ago.

147
00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:10.800
It's absolutely incredible.

148
00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:12.660
They're winding down and they're moving

149
00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:15.693
to a new project called Building Trust.

150
00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:18.663
Very important here.

151
00:06:20.520 --> 00:06:21.960
I can think about in my own career,

152
00:06:21.960 --> 00:06:23.640
I have dismissed three patients

153
00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:26.910
or recommended the three patients I find a new doctor for.

154
00:06:26.910 --> 00:06:28.380
And it was all about trust issues.

155
00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:30.030
They didn't trust me.

156
00:06:30.030 --> 00:06:32.340
And if they're not trusting me,

157
00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:35.670
I didn't feel like I could deliver the best healthcare.

158
00:06:35.670 --> 00:06:37.590
And that's what the next initiative is.

159
00:06:37.590 --> 00:06:39.000
How do we participate in this?

160
00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:40.560
How others are building trust.

161
00:06:40.560 --> 00:06:41.580
And how do we do this

162
00:06:41.580 --> 00:06:43.580
with our other healthcare professionals?

163
00:06:45.240 --> 00:06:46.500
Okay, the AAFP.

164
00:06:46.500 --> 00:06:48.540
They've moved their Choosing wisely to the homepage.

165
00:06:48.540 --> 00:06:52.680
You can find all of their Choosing Wisely statements

166
00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:54.540
on the AAFP website.

167
00:06:54.540 --> 00:06:56.880
American Family Physician, the journal,

168
00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:59.370
they have a Choosing Wisely segment

169
00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:03.393
that they are including now in their monthly journal.

170
00:07:04.710 --> 00:07:08.010
Okay, so here's what the practice recommendations are

171
00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:09.990
in understanding quaternary prevention.

172
00:07:09.990 --> 00:07:12.120
The Choosing Wisely initiative addresses overuse

173
00:07:12.120 --> 00:07:13.890
of tests and treatments.

174
00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:16.650
The goal is informed decision making.

175
00:07:16.650 --> 00:07:18.630
Targeted interventions are needed though

176
00:07:18.630 --> 00:07:22.773
as we help physicians make this change.

177
00:07:24.570 --> 00:07:26.010
Think about this.

178
00:07:26.010 --> 00:07:28.440
Every year in the US,

179
00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:30.510
of all the literature that's published,

180
00:07:30.510 --> 00:07:32.460
only 1% to 2% is ready for me

181
00:07:32.460 --> 00:07:34.500
to use in practice and change the outcome.

182
00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:36.573
Change the outcome for the patient.

183
00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:40.650
Once it's ready, where it will change the outcome,

184
00:07:40.650 --> 00:07:42.423
it takes us 10 years to adopt it.

185
00:07:43.830 --> 00:07:45.123
10 years.

186
00:07:46.380 --> 00:07:48.120
I am reminded of this every day as well

187
00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:48.990
because students come in.

188
00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:50.610
They talk about stuff.

189
00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:54.390
And I'm like, you shouldn't even know about this.

190
00:07:54.390 --> 00:07:57.363
This was changed a decade ago.

191
00:07:59.610 --> 00:08:01.983
Hmm. Inertia.

192
00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:05.130
Be careful because a lot of times, people think,

193
00:08:05.130 --> 00:08:08.850
oh, you know, the patient's gonna be upset about this, okay?

194
00:08:08.850 --> 00:08:13.740
But don't let that hesitation create an undue fear

195
00:08:13.740 --> 00:08:15.990
for implementation here.

196
00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:19.980
And you can find all your Choosing Wisely statements.

197
00:08:19.980 --> 00:08:21.995
The biggest, one of the biggest proponents

198
00:08:21.995 --> 00:08:26.520
of this discussion, besides the ABIM,

199
00:08:26.520 --> 00:08:28.170
is the American College of Radiology.

200
00:08:28.170 --> 00:08:29.640
It's incredible.

201
00:08:29.640 --> 00:08:31.320
They're telling them what not to do.

202
00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:33.246
They make money off this stuff.

203
00:08:33.246 --> 00:08:34.079
AGA.

204
00:08:34.079 --> 00:08:35.790
Don't do colonoscopies if they've had one

205
00:08:35.790 --> 00:08:38.370
within the 10 years and there's no change.

206
00:08:38.370 --> 00:08:40.290
They're telling their members don't do it.

207
00:08:40.290 --> 00:08:41.370
What do I see?

208
00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:44.070
I had a patient who I did a Cologuard on last year.

209
00:08:44.070 --> 00:08:46.200
Went to see GI 'cause I think he's got a stricture

210
00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:47.490
in the esophagus.

211
00:08:47.490 --> 00:08:50.070
They quoted him an 8% false negative rate, and they said,

212
00:08:50.070 --> 00:08:52.980
or they are gonna do a colonoscopy on him.

213
00:08:52.980 --> 00:08:55.110
Ridiculous. He was screened.

214
00:08:55.110 --> 00:08:55.950
We'll take a look at that.

215
00:08:55.950 --> 00:08:58.233
Okay. Now, health promotion.

216
00:08:59.310 --> 00:09:00.960
This is enabling people

217
00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:05.853
to make their best decisions and to take control.

218
00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.780
Now, the population as a whole has to be

219
00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:15.270
in the center of this every single day.

220
00:09:15.270 --> 00:09:17.710
We're not just focusing on an individual

221
00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:20.100
because this is what happens

222
00:09:20.100 --> 00:09:22.383
as we look at the determinants of health.

223
00:09:23.910 --> 00:09:27.660
And wellness is not the absence of disease.

224
00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:28.630
So how do we do this?

225
00:09:28.630 --> 00:09:30.273
Well, we have to restratify.

226
00:09:31.110 --> 00:09:32.970
What is your age?

227
00:09:32.970 --> 00:09:34.230
What is your sex?

228
00:09:34.230 --> 00:09:37.323
What's the family history, which is different than genetic.

229
00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:42.600
You know, for example, 80% of breast cancers are sporadic.

230
00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:47.040
15% to 20% are going to be familial.

231
00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:52.040
Only 3% to 5% are actually genetic, okay?

232
00:09:52.950 --> 00:09:54.603
Socioeconomic data.

233
00:09:55.710 --> 00:09:57.963
It is a determining factor.

234
00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:02.880
Lifestyle choices, environmental factors,

235
00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:04.020
and then, of course, medical issues.

236
00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:04.860
And then we gotta counsel

237
00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:06.990
and we gotta read the patient correctly.

238
00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:09.420
Are they ready to change?

239
00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:11.610
This doesn't have to do just with,

240
00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:13.440
are you ready to stop smoking?

241
00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:15.120
Are you ready to get your blood pressure under control?

242
00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:16.920
Are you ready to get your diabetes under control?

243
00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:20.130
Are you ready to start some type of physical activity?

244
00:10:20.130 --> 00:10:21.300
My question always is,

245
00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:26.300
how many days a week do you think or say this out loud?

246
00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:30.483
Yep, time to go do my exercise.

247
00:10:31.447 --> 00:10:33.090
"Well, Dr. Weismiller, I never say that."

248
00:10:33.090 --> 00:10:34.410
Okay, well we got a place we can start.

249
00:10:34.410 --> 00:10:36.610
What would it be like to say it once a week?

250
00:10:37.560 --> 00:10:38.730
Not that you have to go someplace.

251
00:10:38.730 --> 00:10:41.250
It's just that it's scheduled.

252
00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:43.920
Just like you got here to see me today.

253
00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:45.930
But this requires motivational interviewing.

254
00:10:45.930 --> 00:10:48.033
What am I going to gain from this?

255
00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:52.053
And a lot of education.

256
00:10:52.890 --> 00:10:54.120
A lot of education.

257
00:10:54.120 --> 00:10:55.530
I mean, you think about it.

258
00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:59.973
Of all the self-help measures to help with blood pressure,

259
00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:04.650
cutting back on the sodium, cutting back on alcohol,

260
00:11:04.650 --> 00:11:08.280
physical activity, weight loss has the greatest effect.

261
00:11:08.280 --> 00:11:09.570
It will lower the blood pressure.

262
00:11:09.570 --> 00:11:11.160
If you lose 10 kilos,

263
00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:14.287
it will lower your blood pressure 6 to 20 points.

264
00:11:14.287 --> 00:11:16.107
"I've tried everything."

265
00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:19.987
How many times a week, did you say?

266
00:11:19.987 --> 00:11:20.880
"Oh, I never say that."

267
00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:23.610
Okay, if you're not doing any physical activity, forget it.

268
00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:24.660
You can't lose weight.

269
00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:26.850
Unless you're really drinking six liters

270
00:11:26.850 --> 00:11:28.290
of regular coke a day.

271
00:11:28.290 --> 00:11:30.450
Now, that's a different story.

272
00:11:30.450 --> 00:11:32.790
You know, that's a lot of extra calories you're getting

273
00:11:32.790 --> 00:11:34.743
for no benefit.

274
00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:37.050
Okay, here are the steps

275
00:11:37.050 --> 00:11:38.670
in administering health promotion counseling.

276
00:11:38.670 --> 00:11:40.233
You gotta define the risks.

277
00:11:41.490 --> 00:11:42.690
Are they ready to change?

278
00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:44.580
Advocating the behavior change.

279
00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:47.430
Assisting in identification of some of the target behaviors.

280
00:11:47.430 --> 00:11:51.000
Reinforcing health benefits and offering resources.

281
00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.340
Yeah, go lose 10 kilos.

282
00:11:53.340 --> 00:11:54.783
I'll see you back in a year.

283
00:11:56.677 --> 00:11:57.510
"Well, Dr. Weismiller,

284
00:11:57.510 --> 00:12:00.660
don't you have a medication you can put me on?"

285
00:12:00.660 --> 00:12:02.850
Okay, if something really worked,

286
00:12:02.850 --> 00:12:04.260
wouldn't everybody be on it?

287
00:12:04.260 --> 00:12:05.520
Because most people are not walking

288
00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:06.360
around out there thinking,

289
00:12:06.360 --> 00:12:08.910
I am at the best weight I can be at.

290
00:12:08.910 --> 00:12:11.160
Similar to, we'll take a look in a moment,

291
00:12:11.160 --> 00:12:13.923
if I had something that would make you quit smoking,

292
00:12:14.850 --> 00:12:16.110
wouldn't everybody be on it?

293
00:12:16.110 --> 00:12:17.400
Nobody's walking around out there,

294
00:12:17.400 --> 00:12:19.803
thinking this is the best thing I do.

295
00:12:21.780 --> 00:12:22.833
Now, the USPSTF.

296
00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:26.490
Keep in mind.

297
00:12:26.490 --> 00:12:30.780
We are focused on the published recommendations.

298
00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:32.820
Those are the most current.

299
00:12:32.820 --> 00:12:35.223
Not draft. Published.

300
00:12:36.750 --> 00:12:38.040
With the Affordable Care Act,

301
00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:40.500
if it's a USPSTF A or B recommendation,

302
00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:42.780
your insurance has to cover it.

303
00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:44.730
Now, here are the top 20 recommendations

304
00:12:44.730 --> 00:12:46.890
I see show up most often on the exam.

305
00:12:46.890 --> 00:12:48.240
I would definitely review those.

306
00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:49.863
There are overall a hundred now.

307
00:12:53.190 --> 00:12:55.440
But you need to definitely be aware of these.

308
00:12:57.120 --> 00:12:58.503
So let's try this question.

309
00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:03.720
The number one cause of preventable morbidity

310
00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:05.760
and mortality in the United States today

311
00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:07.770
is which one of the following?

312
00:13:07.770 --> 00:13:12.770
Poverty, tobacco, excessive alcohol use, overweight/obesity.

313
00:13:14.730 --> 00:13:17.550
Which is the number one cause

314
00:13:17.550 --> 00:13:22.053
of preventable morbidity and mortality in the US?

315
00:13:27.420 --> 00:13:29.940
Okay, you know what we call this?

316
00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:31.983
This is a learning opportunity.

317
00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:36.450
'Cause the number one cause of preventable morbidity

318
00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:39.930
and mortality in the US is tobacco.

319
00:13:39.930 --> 00:13:44.313
It is actually the number one cause in the entire world.

320
00:13:45.630 --> 00:13:49.200
Number two, overweight/obesity.

321
00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:51.900
Number three, excessive alcohol.

322
00:13:51.900 --> 00:13:53.670
A study published in the Lancet

323
00:13:53.670 --> 00:13:56.100
in 2022 showed that in the world,

324
00:13:56.100 --> 00:14:00.660
in 2019, 40% of cancers were attributed

325
00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:04.440
to one, two, or those three factors.

326
00:14:04.440 --> 00:14:06.570
40%.

327
00:14:06.570 --> 00:14:09.390
Which may be why by the end of this century,

328
00:14:09.390 --> 00:14:11.430
the World Health Organization says heart disease

329
00:14:11.430 --> 00:14:13.080
will no longer be the number one cause

330
00:14:13.080 --> 00:14:14.280
of death in the world.

331
00:14:14.280 --> 00:14:15.453
It will be cancer.

332
00:14:17.310 --> 00:14:20.133
Okay. Now, tobacco use.

333
00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:24.600
If there's ever a question

334
00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:27.000
where one of the answers is stop smoking,

335
00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:28.920
you don't need to read the question.

336
00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:30.646
Just choose it.

337
00:14:30.646 --> 00:14:32.310
(audience laughing)

338
00:14:32.310 --> 00:14:37.310
Almost every known disease is made worse with tobacco.

339
00:14:37.410 --> 00:14:40.230
There are very few exceptions.

340
00:14:40.230 --> 00:14:42.090
And there are.

341
00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:44.220
However, you'll still die

342
00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:46.440
of your lung cancer or your heart disease

343
00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:49.230
before you die of that other thing, which gets better.

344
00:14:49.230 --> 00:14:51.210
Okay, overweight/obesity.

345
00:14:51.210 --> 00:14:53.670
Dr. Vale's gonna talk completely about that.

346
00:14:53.670 --> 00:14:55.290
I just wanna remind you that in adults,

347
00:14:55.290 --> 00:14:58.410
it's a BMI greater than or equal to 25 for overweight,

348
00:14:58.410 --> 00:15:00.600
greater than or equal to 30 for obese.

349
00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:02.340
She's gonna talk completely about that.

350
00:15:02.340 --> 00:15:04.050
And then excessive alcohol use.

351
00:15:04.050 --> 00:15:08.790
Let's take a look at issues related to these three things.

352
00:15:08.790 --> 00:15:10.290
Now, do keep in mind.

353
00:15:10.290 --> 00:15:12.450
When we talk about kids who are overweight,

354
00:15:12.450 --> 00:15:13.800
it's a percentile.

355
00:15:13.800 --> 00:15:16.170
Overweight is greater than or equal

356
00:15:16.170 --> 00:15:18.840
to the 85th percentile up to the 95th.

357
00:15:18.840 --> 00:15:22.233
Obese, greater than or equal to the 95th percentile.

358
00:15:23.340 --> 00:15:27.450
Now, here are some of the highest ranked services.

359
00:15:27.450 --> 00:15:30.630
Big bang for the buck with low delivery rates.

360
00:15:30.630 --> 00:15:33.870
And one of those is tobacco cessation counseling to adults.

361
00:15:33.870 --> 00:15:37.200
I'm always amazed at the number of patients in our practice

362
00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:39.480
where I look at their problem list,

363
00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:41.970
and they smoke and they're overweight or obese,

364
00:15:41.970 --> 00:15:44.310
and that's not even on the problem list.

365
00:15:44.310 --> 00:15:48.630
What's on there is cough, acute knee pain.

366
00:15:48.630 --> 00:15:50.130
And somebody put that on their wellness exam.

367
00:15:50.130 --> 00:15:53.280
I mean, okay, I don't need to know that on the problem list.

368
00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:54.270
Okay?

369
00:15:54.270 --> 00:15:55.680
Now, tobacco use.

370
00:15:55.680 --> 00:15:57.690
As we said, leading cause.

371
00:15:57.690 --> 00:16:01.860
Some daily smokers appear to be smoking fewer cigarettes.

372
00:16:01.860 --> 00:16:04.830
You decrease your risk of lung cancer by smoking fewer.

373
00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:06.600
Heart disease only by,

374
00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:09.360
decreased by smoking none.

375
00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:10.770
We know that sustained,

376
00:16:10.770 --> 00:16:14.280
adequately funded comprehensive state tobacco programs lead

377
00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:16.503
to further reduction in smoking.

378
00:16:17.662 --> 00:16:20.490
480,000 deaths per year.

379
00:16:20.490 --> 00:16:22.320
Every day, about 1,600 young people

380
00:16:22.320 --> 00:16:25.740
under the age of 18 try smoking.

381
00:16:25.740 --> 00:16:29.220
200 of those are gonna become daily smokers.

382
00:16:29.220 --> 00:16:30.960
One of five US adults continue

383
00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:33.210
to use some form of tobacco product.

384
00:16:33.210 --> 00:16:34.597
Look at the cost.

385
00:16:34.597 --> 00:16:37.170
$300 billion each year,

386
00:16:37.170 --> 00:16:41.700
including more than $225 billion in direct medical costs.

387
00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:43.710
It's an enormous issue.

388
00:16:43.710 --> 00:16:46.680
Here's the USPSTF in January of 2021.

389
00:16:46.680 --> 00:16:50.520
Recommends the clinicians ask all adults about tobacco use.

390
00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:52.680
Advise them to stop smoking

391
00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:54.420
and provide behavioral interventions

392
00:16:54.420 --> 00:16:59.220
and US FDA-approved pharmacotherapy.

393
00:16:59.220 --> 00:17:00.750
Pregnant women, we do the same thing.

394
00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:02.670
It's just we don't offer the pharmacotherapy.

395
00:17:02.670 --> 00:17:05.073
We just don't have adequate data.

396
00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:09.030
What about electronic nicotine delivery systems?

397
00:17:09.030 --> 00:17:11.670
The data is still an I recommendation

398
00:17:11.670 --> 00:17:14.100
in terms of does it help

399
00:17:14.100 --> 00:17:16.710
with decreasing or stopping smoking.

400
00:17:16.710 --> 00:17:17.700
We've got issues related

401
00:17:17.700 --> 00:17:19.410
to effectiveness and safety, which we don't know.

402
00:17:19.410 --> 00:17:21.840
So it continues to be a category I.

403
00:17:21.840 --> 00:17:23.790
As we look at children and adolescents,

404
00:17:23.790 --> 00:17:25.110
we wanna prevent initiation.

405
00:17:25.110 --> 00:17:30.090
And therefore, we have to at least include education

406
00:17:30.090 --> 00:17:34.290
and brief counseling to prevent initiation.

407
00:17:34.290 --> 00:17:35.970
Very important.

408
00:17:35.970 --> 00:17:38.073
School age adolescents.

409
00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:41.190
B recommendation.

410
00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:43.800
Cessation, it's an I recommendation

411
00:17:43.800 --> 00:17:46.800
when you're looking at school age children and adolescents.

412
00:17:46.800 --> 00:17:48.300
It's not that you shouldn't quit.

413
00:17:48.300 --> 00:17:50.120
It's just we don't data that supports it.

414
00:17:50.120 --> 00:17:52.920
It intuitively makes sense though.

415
00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:54.783
Now, what's this by the numbers?

416
00:17:55.920 --> 00:17:59.133
One half of people who smoke will try to quit each year.

417
00:18:00.030 --> 00:18:02.943
Only 1 in 20 will have abstinence beyond six months.

418
00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:07.500
About 2% to 3% who attempt to stop smoking will quit

419
00:18:07.500 --> 00:18:10.323
with no pharmacological or behavioral intervention.

420
00:18:11.550 --> 00:18:13.650
You gotta have this.

421
00:18:13.650 --> 00:18:17.913
Now, as we look at smoking cessation and intervention.

422
00:18:18.810 --> 00:18:21.930
First-line drugs if you smoke more than a half pack per day.

423
00:18:21.930 --> 00:18:23.880
Less than half pack per day, is it benefit?

424
00:18:23.880 --> 00:18:24.713
We don't know.

425
00:18:26.340 --> 00:18:27.450
Clinical interventions.

426
00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:28.890
Me talking with you for as little

427
00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:30.753
as three minutes makes a difference.

428
00:18:31.770 --> 00:18:33.900
And if you combine behavior

429
00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:36.720
with smoking cessation pharmacotherapy,

430
00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:38.580
you improve your cessation rates.

431
00:18:38.580 --> 00:18:42.750
Now, there are three FDA approved medications.

432
00:18:42.750 --> 00:18:45.060
There's nicotine replacement therapy.

433
00:18:45.060 --> 00:18:46.110
There's bupropion.

434
00:18:46.110 --> 00:18:47.610
And there's varenicline.

435
00:18:47.610 --> 00:18:48.750
Psychosocial therapy,

436
00:18:48.750 --> 00:18:51.573
behavioral therapy are critically important here.

437
00:18:53.040 --> 00:18:54.360
Now, before you throw up your hands

438
00:18:54.360 --> 00:18:56.520
and say, "Oh, they don't work,"

439
00:18:56.520 --> 00:18:59.400
ask your patient when they come in and say nothing works.

440
00:18:59.400 --> 00:19:01.100
Well, how'd you get started on it?

441
00:19:01.980 --> 00:19:05.433
Because none of these medications will make you quit.

442
00:19:07.170 --> 00:19:08.220
They're designed for people

443
00:19:08.220 --> 00:19:10.773
who have quit to help them through withdrawal.

444
00:19:11.887 --> 00:19:13.533
"Well, I went to my doctor,

445
00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:17.310
and I said I really wanna quit smoking, but I can't.

446
00:19:17.310 --> 00:19:18.270
So give me something.

447
00:19:18.270 --> 00:19:19.500
And they gave me something and it didn't work."

448
00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:20.640
Well, of course it's not gonna work.

449
00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:22.530
I could told you that before you got started.

450
00:19:22.530 --> 00:19:25.050
That's not how it's designed, okay?

451
00:19:25.050 --> 00:19:27.243
They're designed for people who have quit.

452
00:19:29.850 --> 00:19:32.310
Being in the hospital, I have not decided to quit.

453
00:19:32.310 --> 00:19:34.050
Somebody has forced me to quit

454
00:19:34.050 --> 00:19:35.900
'cause I can't smoke in the hospital.

455
00:19:37.860 --> 00:19:40.380
The residents are always like beside themselves with me

456
00:19:40.380 --> 00:19:42.480
'cause I'm like, if they can get up

457
00:19:42.480 --> 00:19:44.040
and go outside and smoke, let 'em smoke.

458
00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:45.630
I mean, I can't make 'em quit.

459
00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:47.340
I can advise you should quit.

460
00:19:47.340 --> 00:19:49.620
But me forcing you to stay in your bed

461
00:19:49.620 --> 00:19:52.503
and not going out to smoke does not help you, okay?

462
00:19:53.550 --> 00:19:55.350
Okay, here are the behavioral changes.

463
00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:57.960
It's rarely gonna be a single event.

464
00:19:57.960 --> 00:19:59.970
It's a gradual process.

465
00:19:59.970 --> 00:20:02.460
Think about anything you've had to change.

466
00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:04.020
Motivational interviewing?

467
00:20:04.020 --> 00:20:05.730
Stages of change model.

468
00:20:05.730 --> 00:20:06.750
The 5 As.

469
00:20:06.750 --> 00:20:08.550
Ask, advise, assess, assist, arrange.

470
00:20:08.550 --> 00:20:11.220
Any of them can be possible.

471
00:20:11.220 --> 00:20:13.263
The one I use most often is the 5 As.

472
00:20:14.430 --> 00:20:17.010
But I also do motivational interviewing.

473
00:20:17.010 --> 00:20:20.373
How do I move somebody to that action stage?

474
00:20:21.690 --> 00:20:25.470
Now, telephone quit-lines, they work.

475
00:20:25.470 --> 00:20:27.633
It's 3:00 AM. I want to smoke.

476
00:20:29.010 --> 00:20:31.350
Who do I call?

477
00:20:31.350 --> 00:20:32.730
Not Ghostbusters.

478
00:20:32.730 --> 00:20:34.353
I need the telephone quit-line.

479
00:20:35.790 --> 00:20:38.460
It offers additional benefit when I combine it

480
00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:42.243
with physician advice and pharmacotherapy.

481
00:20:43.590 --> 00:20:46.170
Okay, let's try this question.

482
00:20:46.170 --> 00:20:48.060
Which of the following is true regarding the use

483
00:20:48.060 --> 00:20:50.670
of antidepressants for smoking cessation?

484
00:20:50.670 --> 00:20:52.140
Bupropion may only be used

485
00:20:52.140 --> 00:20:54.930
as monotherapy for smoking cessation.

486
00:20:54.930 --> 00:20:57.990
It's unsafe to use in patients with heart disease.

487
00:20:57.990 --> 00:20:59.970
The United States Public Health Service guidelines

488
00:20:59.970 --> 00:21:03.063
on tobacco cessation recommend the use of SSRIs.

489
00:21:03.990 --> 00:21:06.060
The guidelines on tobacco cessation recommend

490
00:21:06.060 --> 00:21:08.730
against the use of all tricyclics.

491
00:21:08.730 --> 00:21:10.710
Or bupropion is contraindicated

492
00:21:10.710 --> 00:21:12.560
in a patient with an eating disorder.

493
00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:20.880
Okay, excellent.

494
00:21:20.880 --> 00:21:22.710
E is the correct answer.

495
00:21:22.710 --> 00:21:24.390
E is the correct answer.

496
00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:25.710
Bupropion is contraindicated

497
00:21:25.710 --> 00:21:27.720
in patients with an eating disorder.

498
00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:29.730
Okay, so here's smoking cessation.

499
00:21:29.730 --> 00:21:30.960
First line.

500
00:21:30.960 --> 00:21:31.980
Nicotine replacement.

501
00:21:31.980 --> 00:21:33.990
Bupropion or varenicline.

502
00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:38.610
Now, in general, most third party payers have wanted you

503
00:21:38.610 --> 00:21:40.920
to fail nicotine replacement and bupropion

504
00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:42.670
before they'll approve varenicline.

505
00:21:43.530 --> 00:21:44.760
The controllers.

506
00:21:44.760 --> 00:21:48.540
Bupropion, varenicline, or a nicotine patch.

507
00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:50.310
And then the relievers.

508
00:21:50.310 --> 00:21:52.893
The gum, lozenge, inhaler, or nasal spray.

509
00:21:53.850 --> 00:21:56.040
Now, keep in mind, a lot of people don't know

510
00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:57.573
how to use the gum correctly.

511
00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:02.700
It's not something you chew like Bubblicious, okay?

512
00:22:02.700 --> 00:22:04.470
What you do is you chew it

513
00:22:04.470 --> 00:22:06.840
until you start to get that tingling sensation

514
00:22:06.840 --> 00:22:09.000
i.e. that means the nicotine is being released.

515
00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.010
And then you park it.

516
00:22:11.010 --> 00:22:12.690
You put it between your cheek and your gum

517
00:22:12.690 --> 00:22:15.060
and it just sits there, okay?

518
00:22:15.060 --> 00:22:16.680
And then when you get that urge again,

519
00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:18.960
you pull it back out and chew a couple more times

520
00:22:18.960 --> 00:22:22.320
so you start getting that tingling sensation again, okay?

521
00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:26.310
So as we look at how we use controllers,

522
00:22:26.310 --> 00:22:27.810
they are going to be helpful

523
00:22:27.810 --> 00:22:30.420
in reducing the impulse to smoke.

524
00:22:30.420 --> 00:22:35.420
Relievers work in managing those acute cravings, okay?

525
00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:40.110
Now, second line agents.

526
00:22:40.110 --> 00:22:42.090
These are, neither of these gonna be FDA approved.

527
00:22:42.090 --> 00:22:43.770
But nortriptyline can be used.

528
00:22:43.770 --> 00:22:46.023
And clonidine can be used.

529
00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:50.730
If I'm concerned about any given individuals,

530
00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:51.843
these are the groups.

531
00:22:53.130 --> 00:22:54.600
Medical contraindications,

532
00:22:54.600 --> 00:22:57.210
I'm not smoking a lot, pregnant or breastfeeding,

533
00:22:57.210 --> 00:22:58.290
and adolescent smokers.

534
00:22:58.290 --> 00:23:00.540
Those, we just don't have really a lot of data

535
00:23:00.540 --> 00:23:03.210
on what is going to work in these individuals

536
00:23:03.210 --> 00:23:05.490
and/or no studies ever gonna be done.

537
00:23:05.490 --> 00:23:07.170
